===Proper noun===
'''Pict'''

# A member of an ancient people of northern [[Scotland]].

==Etymology==
<!--from [[en:Picts]]-->
The [[Greek language|Greek]] word ''Πικτοί'' ([[Latin]] ''Picti'') first appears in a [[panegyric]] written by Eumenius in AD 297 and is taken to mean "painted or tattooed people" (Latin ''pingere'' "paint").  This may, however, be due to early folk etymology and the term likely has a Celtic origin, perhaps ''Pehta, Peihta'' (meaning "fighters") <ref>www.etymonline.com</ref>.  

The [[Gael]]s of en:Ireland and Dál Riata called the Picts ''Cruithne'', (Old Irish ''cru(i)then-túath''), presumably from Proto-Celtic *''k<sup>w</sup>riteno-toutā''.  There were also ''Cruithne'' in [[Ulster]], in particular the kings of Dál nAraidi.<ref>The ''Cruithne'' are discussed by Byrne, ''Irish Kings and High-Kings'', pp. 106–109, Ó Cróinín, ''Early Medieval Ireland'', pp. 48–50.</ref> The [[Briton]]s (later the [[Welsh]] and [[Cornish]]) in the south knew them, in the P-Celtic form of "Cruithne", as ''Prydyn''; the terms "[[Britain]]" and "Briton" come from the same root.<ref>Old Irish ''cruth'' and Welsh ''pryd'' are the Q- and P-Celtic forms respectively of a word meaning "form" or "shape": taken to be a reference to  the Picts' practice of tattooing their bodies. See [http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/institutes/sassi/spns/INDEX2CH.pdf The Scottish Place-Name Society] and [http://www.ceantar.org/Dicts/MB2/mb11.html MacBain's Dictionary].</ref> Their Old English name gave the modern Scots form ''Pechts''. <ref>The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle has ''pihtas'' and ''pehtas''.</ref>  

